In Ruby, freeze is built-in.
deep_freeze is not built-in in core Ruby — it’s usually custom-written (or provided by libraries like Rails).

Let’s understand clearly from scratch.

1️⃣ freeze in Ruby

freeze makes an object immutable (cannot be modified).

str = "hello"
str.freeze

str << " world"   # ❌ FrozenError
Important:

freeze only freezes the object itself, NOT nested objects.

🔎 Example — Freeze is Shallow
arr = [[1,2], [3,4]]
arr.freeze

arr << [5,6]      # ❌ Not allowed
arr[0] << 3       # ✅ Allowed

Why?

arr is frozen

But inner arrays are NOT frozen

So freeze is shallow.

2️⃣ deep_freeze

Ruby does NOT provide deep_freeze by default.

It means:

Freeze the object AND everything inside it recursively.

Example custom implementation:

class Object
  def deep_freeze
    freeze
  end
end

class Array
  def deep_freeze
    each(&:deep_freeze)
    freeze
  end
end

class Hash
  def deep_freeze
    each do |k, v|
      k.deep_freeze
      v.deep_freeze
    end
    freeze
  end
end
🔎 Example — Deep Freeze
arr = [[1,2], [3,4]]
arr.deep_freeze

arr[0] << 3   # ❌ FrozenError

Now even nested objects are frozen.

3️⃣ Side-by-Side Difference
Feature	freeze	deep_freeze
Built into Ruby?	✅ Yes	❌ No (custom/lib)
Freezes main object	✅ Yes	✅ Yes
Freezes nested objects	❌ No	✅ Yes
Shallow or deep	Shallow	Deep
4️⃣ Why Deep Freeze Is Useful

Used when:

Defining constants

Config objects

Immutable data structures

Prevent accidental modification

Example:

CONFIG = {
  db: { host: "localhost" }
}.deep_freeze

Now no one can accidentally change config.

5️⃣ Important Note (Rails)

In Rails 7+, there is:

Object#deep_dup

But still no built-in deep_freeze in Ruby core.

🎯 Simple Summary

freeze → lock only the outer box

deep_freeze → lock the box and everything inside

